2019: it’s still about time, trust and transparency

Article by Nigel Dalton
Published on 4th Mar 2019 — Read in 5 mins

Share

  • Tweet about it
  • Share this on LinkedIn
  • Share this on Facebook

We are nearly 15% into 2019, and I’ve reached that annoying stage of the year where the summer holidays are becoming a distant memory. For me, summer 2019 involved long warm days in New Zealand, watching groups of tweens battle it out on Fortnite.

I’m in awe of this global gaming phenomenon. With 60 million players at its peak, untold revenues, Fortnite is the source of countless family disputes, and a similar numbers of lawsuits over rights to bizarre victory dances. Surely it won’t be long until it stops just being a millennial craze, and seeps into how we all connect day-to-day. Will we start to see that emerge this year on the web? Maybe not, but lets bookmark that for my 2020 thoughts. For now, 2019 remains a year of time, trust and transparency in the tech landscape.

How will tech save us time? How will it foster trust between people? And how will it be more transparent with data? There are technologies that make this better, and there are technologies that make this worse.

Artificial intelligence (AI)

Artificial intelligence is no longer science fiction or a purely academic pursuit – it is impacting everyone’s life and being adopted into businesses around the world. Just earlier this year, we saw the announcement of Mia, UBank’s third foray into AI for banking – to make applying for a mortgage more millennial.

At REA, we dipped our toes into the AI world last year and since then the technology has made huge leaps and bounds. My team at REALABS continues to look into new ways we can work with the computer to make property searching, selling and styling easier. Our customised Anki Vector mini-robot is sassy, interactive, and smart. Although, connected to Amazon Alexa, she claims the Prime Minister of Australia is Malcolm Turnbull. That said, I haven’t #factchecked today.

AI has been made possible by ever-cheaper computing costs using cloud servers at Amazon and Google – enabling massive processing, and large-scale data storage. It’s like panning for gold – in 2010 we each had little gold pans looking for customer data nuggets in side-creeks, one at a time. Now we have gigantic industrial data dredges filtering whole rivers of consumer data to find the gold. 90% of the world’s stored data was created in the last 12 months!

It will get less weird to be caught talking to your computer in 2019 – their ability to listen to, process, comprehend context, translate and provide smart answers back will start to make “hey Siri”, “hey Google” or “hey Mercedes” second nature for us.

Virtual reality (VR)

The most exciting development in this space will be smaller, smarter cameras to capture 3D images. Where once upon a time, low-cost and high-quality were sworn enemies, this is about to change.

Cameras that capture 3D environments that fit in your pocket will make virtual reality virtually doable by anyone, anywhere. The first phones that can do this are emerging from Samsung in 2019.

This is especially pertinent at REA Group, where we live and breathe property. Better 3D cameras means you can capture a 3D tour of a home and upload it much more quickly than ever before. In the absence of time travel (which may only be a matter of time until it’s here), VR will allow people to inspect multiple homes on a Saturday morning without getting stuck in traffic. This excites us!

Augmented reality (AR)

The biggest trend in AR this year is focused on saving time – and that is, the proliferation of smarter avatars.

At REALABS we’re experimenting with this in a real estate context: creating avatars of real estate agents or property managers that can answer questions using smart assistant technology.

We will start to see technologies combine. Where avatars were once strictly for gaming, we are seeing more headset-friendly consumers wanting a digital version of themselves – their ‘digital twin’. We can apply that to business, make it intelligent by attaching AI technology (Siri etc), and then Bob’s your virtual uncle. An agent avatar in a 3D tour is very possible.

Expect to meet a lot more digital people in 2019. Think I’m joking? In Japan last year, the first people started marrying their augmented reality avatar friends. That is how deeply we will become connected to our computer-generated world.

Internet of Things (iOT)

It’s been the talk of the town for a few years now, but we’ve yet to see it fully take off. In part it’s because so many connected devices have been operating on closed operating systems, and this is what will change.

We’ll start to see more integration across operating systems and devices – whether it’s your security system talking to your vacuum cleaner, or your fridge talking to your local supermarket – connecting them intelligently is the mission for 2019.

What else will impact tech in 2019?

If you’re in a lucky neighbourhood, the early arrival of 5G phones and networks will make rich content king again. Video will flow easily, at higher resolutions, and enable really heavy media like augmented and virtual reality possible. A 500mb house tour file could take less than a second. Forget email, you’ll need to send a talking video clip with GIFs replacing static emojis.

This is not mainstream yet, it will take Apple or Google to produce a 5G device for that to happen.

Fakes of everything will become the norm, including faked people – and thus, we will become much more suspicious online. According to Edelman’s latest Trust Barometer, 68% of Australians are most afraid of cyber-security. Identify theft is already rampant and people are going to need to up their game around passwords. Take the extra time when logging into important computer systems by using longer passwords and a second validation by text message to confirm your identity (called 2-factor authentication). Definitely get a Password ‘keeper’ on your phone, and use little sentences as passwords, to make them longer.

And what about the Fortnite-playing generation of VR-tweens I mentioned? Headsets on, collaborating online, chatting, bantering and achieving ‘work’ together across continents. They are virtual reality natives, who expect everything to happen NOW. You can only imagine the millennial expectation of customer service! Gaming as a user interface design is coming to mobile apps and websites, but it will be less about combating, more about collecting and collaborating for a shared goal – gather your weapons for some co-operative PVP interior decorating!
